      "writtenOn": "2021-04-12T19:06:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Major: `reservedDuration` \u0026\u0026 SubmitQueueNotReleased extra state smells to me.\n\nI think you can avoid both entirely and just do this:\n  \nerr :\u003d datastore.RunInTransaction(ctx, func(ctx context.Context){\n  submit.Release(ctx, s.runID)\n  notifySubmissionCompleted(ctx, s.runID, sc) // don\u0027t dispatch\n})\n// TODO: optimization for happy path\nreturn eventspb.DispatchNow(ctx)",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 296,
        "startChar": 1,
        "endLine": 304,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "0b987a05197c4ceb054885bbb74114a48ced8247",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8ca0f8c1_44d75e29",
        "filename": "cv/internal/run/impl/handler/submit.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 304,
      "author": {
        "id": 1381059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-04-13T01:14:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think the intention of SubmitQueueNotReleased is to reduce the latency to notify RM when release failure occurs. Without this, it\u0027s likely that RM would have to wait for the submit deadline naturally expires before it figures out something went wrong during submission. However, if release fails, then mostly notifySubmissionCompeleted(without dispatch) will fail as well because they are mostly datastore operations. Therefore, I think what you\u0027ve proposed makes better sense and is indeed much simpler.",
      "parentUuid": "a660b52b_3226020b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 296,
        "startChar": 1,
        "endLine": 304,
        "endChar": 51
      },
